MSS announces protocol to find obesity genes
Social Security conducts a research to discover the gender of obesity in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it would conduct an investigation to discover the gender of obesity in children and young people, called the Protocol 'Genetics of Obesity of Childhood and Adolescence', which would allow to be associated with overweight markers.
In a communiqué, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialities of the National Medical Centre of the 21st Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by experts and postgraduate students of the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Political Institute (IGN).
The research calls for participation in the population whether or not it is legal, to visit the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out for minors, all Saturdays from 8:00.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of Mexico Pontient) and that since 8 October, the activity has been carried out in the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Unit (State of Mexico East).
Once the goal of meeting 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independent Sports Unit (South of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (North of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research was to know the components and importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in children and young Mexicans to prevent chronic degenerative diseases.
On 14 November, the World Diabetes Day required that the goal be to gather three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14 with the consent and supervision of their parents for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about the physical activity and history of hereditary diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger sufferings such as diabetes or kidney failure.
It detailed that Saturdays apply to all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure taking, glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (it is sought to identify genes associated with infant obesity).
Cruz López noted that this research is in the interest of health professionals because of the alarming increase in weight in minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of children, of 77 per cent in obesity, and of 47 per cent in girls; in terms of overweight, a dramatic increase was also observed', the IMSS specialist highlighted.
It indicated that the justification for the search for markers is that the population of the country differs from others because of their genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 per cent of American Indian heritage, 30 per cent European and five per cent African, and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calorie) and that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive assessment of children, which allows them to detect whether they are overweight or obese.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-coloured patches (acantosis) in the neck and antebrasis, which indicate the probability of metabolic and even prediabetes changes.
The information is handled in a confidential manner, the doctors hand it to the parents in writing, who are explained to each of the measurements and changes in the lifestyle they must make to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic suffering: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, remain most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use transport means instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to high caloric intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and genetics analysed in this protocol.
UNAM's asphalt would avoid bays
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Chemicals Faculty, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of the environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals sent to the floor were met, it would not be necessary to repair about 200 thousand basins each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the UNAM Chemicals Faculty (FQ), who assured that if the construction and maintenance process of an asphalt floor is the right, the basins could be reduced in quantity or, even, completely eliminated.
At his conference A technological opinion of the baches, dictated in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, revealed that the laboratory in charge develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believed that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, like some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and therefore the formation of basins.
He explained that asphalt, the hardest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbons molecules, some high molecular weights, called asphalts, and others of low molecular weights, called maltens, which together give the floor its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of the asphalt is that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves as a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrade it has a nearly solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes fragile, added.
The above means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform, but that it is changing during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the specialist in chemical engineering warned.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible flooring, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, consisting of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that constitute the folder, he pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
When passing the vehicles and making efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well on the floor.
If it were modified asphalt they would spread even better, the chemical engineer felt.
