The North Stream, new Russian gas entrance door in Europe
The North Stream pipeline, which directly communicates Western Europe with Russia through the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must provide gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian giant of the gas, has wanted to celebrate the event with great pump.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the Baltic coast, between orchestra music and a delicate buffet, at the opening of the North Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly under the sea, Russia and Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands, Mark Rutte, have turned together the valve wheel that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western Europe network.
With this new pipeline, every year will reach 27.5 million cubic metres of additional Russian gas to Western Europe through a first wave of 1,224 km that communicate the San Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed by the end of 2012 which will provide a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, i.e. enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, the possibility of building a third tube through the same route is already discussed.
For Gazprom, the time-continuation of this huge work presents the areas of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had firmly opposed the project.
In fact, the North Stream will allow direct supply of gas to Germany, avoiding land transit by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
These two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening it to close access to Western European markets.
At the point of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe's energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has known, in just five years, to triumph its vision of a direct partnership between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
"This pipeline is a component of our association with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically," said François Fillon during the opening of the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the major gas sector contracts are both political and economical.
All of this explains the wide smiles in the faces of the Gazprom directors, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-covered steel to protect it from the anchors of the ships.
It is supported at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mine fields dating from World War II.
"It was necessary to withdraw or destroy a hundred of them, by caution," says Jens Müller, spokesperson of Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to extend the protection measures for fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted all its length: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was provided for in Sweden's waters, but the project's managers gave up on the same ground as the Swedishs were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to be permanently established in the sea in front of their backs.
"If I had, we would have interrupted the gas passage in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of escape, the gas of the pipeline will be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that a flight will take place, since they have planned joints that, according to the forecasts, will have a flight every 100,000 years.
The control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by a submarine robot, drawn by a ship, carrying out external inspections, as well as by a device passing through the interior of the pipeline.
With the shape of a pure, it enters the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of a meter, and moves with the gas.
At its arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides precise data on possible metal distortions.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without the need for any type of repair.
The flow of the gas is guaranteed by pressure only.
At first, it is 200 bars and, at the end of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined their forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which has 51% of the stakes.
To her, the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and exploiting the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented this company, for a renewable period of twenty-five years, the total capacity of gas transport.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline has been completed by 30% with the contribution of shareholders and by 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should be EUR 7,400 million for the two pipes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are certain that they will not exceed their investment, since Gazprom assumes the risk of spending on its own.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy shore planted with pines.
Some valves, with 4.5 meters high, form the gas output door.
There are some sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas to arrive before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
Total capacity will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
