Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are seeking employment.
The XV Week for the employment of disabled people starts today.
Despite a resolved public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among persons with disabilities doubles the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the population as a whole.
Dissolved?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people.
"The progress made for fifteen years has been considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there's still a lot to be done."
It should be noted that the unemployed continue to face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are over 50 years old (a 17% average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not finished the bachelor's degree and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53 per cent for the disabled, compared to 38 per cent of the average.
In other words, there are numerous issues that make it particularly difficult to return to the labour world and that "conform the problem," says Christian Grapin, Director-General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help businesses hire disabled workers.
These are the target obstacles.
Moreover, there are those who are not mentioned; the minds of the people advance, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Enterprise Association for the City pointed out that the directors surveyed had "a level of knowledge about low disability", with an "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physical or intellectual disabilities".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, which was set out in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, which date from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
"Now we reach around 3%," said Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting the contributions of companies that do not respect this law.
The test: the number of establishment "subjected to this contribution", as well as the disbursed amounts, has decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, has generated great pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a true awareness, especially among the major groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies with between 20 and 49 workers have employees with disabilities in their schedule, compared to 82 per cent of enterprises with between 100 and 199 workers.
